This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with extractive summarization, which is a natural language processing task. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of linguistically informed features, which is a common approach in NLP. 

The paper also involves modeling sentence prominence and pairwise repulsion, which are concepts related to information retrieval and machine learning. Therefore, it could also belong to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories. 

The use of deep contextualized representations suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category, which deals with the development of intelligent agents that can learn from data. 

Finally, the paper involves probabilistic modeling, which is a common approach in the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category.
